{"id":"max-runs-001","rule_id":"spec.max-runs-last-call-wins","severity":"HIGH","file":"schedule/__init__.py","line":715,"message":"The budget is checked only after job_func executes. After one run under max_runs(3), changing the same job to max_runs(1) and invoking run_all() executes the function a second time before cancellation. This violates last-call-wins and the invariant that the (n+1)-th execution never happens.","confidence":"high"}
{"id":"max-runs-002","rule_id":"spec.actual-execution-counting","severity":"HIGH","file":"schedule/__init__.py","line":708,"message":"The counter increments only after job_func returns. If a max_runs(1) function raises, it was called but _run_count remains 0 and the job remains scheduled; a second scheduler invocation calls it again. This violates the requirement to count when Job.run() actually calls job_func and permits an (n+1)-th execution.","confidence":"high"}
{"id":"max-runs-003","rule_id":"consistency.stale-run-docstring","severity":"LOW","file":"schedule/__init__.py","line":698,"message":"Job.run's return documentation says CancelJob is returned when the deadline is reached, but run-budget exhaustion now also returns CancelJob. The public method documentation no longer describes all cancellation outcomes.","confidence":"high"}
